## Why This Is Asked

Tests practical understanding of immutable retention and governance controls in AWS, not just concepts.

## Key Concepts

- S3 Object Lock with Governance vs Compliance modes
- Per-prefix retention via Lambda using PutObjectRetention on uploads
- IAM policy boundaries including s3:BypassGovernanceRetention for overrides
- Audit and verification using CloudTrail and AWS Config

## Code Example

```javascript
// Placeholder for AWS SDK usage to apply retention (JS/Node.js v3)
import { S3Client, PutObjectRetentionCommand } from '@aws-sdk/client-s3';
const client = new S3Client({ region: 'us-east-1' });
const cmd = new PutObjectRetentionCommand({
  Bucket: 'reglake-bucket',
  Key: 'regulated/record1.csv',
  Retention: { Mode: 'GOVERNANCE', RetainUntilDate: new Date('2033-01-01T00:00:00Z') }
});
await client.send(cmd);
```

## Follow-up Questions

- How would you test during CI to ensure retention is enforced on all future uploads?
- How would you design an audit trail to prove no data was deleted or overwritten during the governance override window?

## Why This Is Asked

Tests practical ability to apply basic AWS guardrails in a real-world multi-team setup.

## Key Concepts

- IAM least privilege with per-prefix access
- S3 bucket policy enforcement for encryption and public access
- Event-driven validation with Lambda on PutObject
- Observability via CloudWatch

## Code Example

```javascript
// Minimal Lambda skeleton to validate encryption and prefix
exports.handler = async (event) => {
  const r = event.Records[0];
  const bucket = r.s3.bucket.name;
  const key = r.s3.object.key;
  const enc = r.s3.object.serverSideEncryption;
  if (!enc) throw new Error("Object not encrypted");
  if (!/^corp-logs\/team-(a|b|c)\//.test(key)) throw new Error("Wrong prefix");
  return;
}
```

## Follow-up Questions

- How would you scale this pattern for more teams?
- How would you test revocation and auditing of access?

## Why This Is Asked
Assesses design for fair throughput, scalability, and auditable enforcement in a shared data lake.

## Key Concepts
- Per-tenant quotas; token bucket; API Gateway usage plans; DynamoDB; Lambda; S3 prefixes; CloudWatch; Kinesis Firehose; testing at scale.

## Code Example
```javascript
class TokenBucket {
  constructor(rate, burst) {
    this.rate = rate; // tokens per second
    this.burst = burst;
    this.tokens = burst;
    this.last = Date.now();
  }
  allow(n=1){
    const now = Date.now();
    const elapsed = (now - this.last) / 1000;
    this.tokens = Math.min(this.burst, this.tokens + elapsed * this.rate);
    this.last = now;
    if (this.tokens >= n) { this.tokens -= n; return true; }
    return false;
  }
}
```

## Follow-up Questions
- How would you test multi-tenant fairness under bursty conditions and validate SLA guarantees?
- What changes if large tenants typically spike during business hours?

